title: Two-thirds of returning ISIS brides headed to Victoria | 7NEWS
description: Reports indicate two-thirds of ISIS brides seeking to return to Australia from a Syrian camp will be resettled in Victoria. The Victorian government has not confirmed specific numbers, stating applications are assessed individually, while NSW Premier Chris Minns revealed approximately one-third of 11 brides and 23 children will return to New South Wales. State and federal governments are conducting meetings to determine reintegration strategies, particularly regarding medical care and education for the children. title: Australia backs removal of Andrew from royal succession amid Epstein files scandal | 7NEWS
description: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has written to UK Prime Minister Keir Starmer supporting the removal of Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor from the Royal Line of Succession following his arrest on suspicion of sharing confidential government documents with sex trafficker Jeffrey Epstein. Australia is the first of 14 Commonwealth countries required to agree to such a change. The federal government has committed an additional $230 million to planning for high-speed rail between Newcastle and Sydney, with travel times expected to be reduced to one hour and the project creating nearly 100,000 jobs over five decades. title: Residents tackle fleeing teen after Middle Park crash | 7NEWS
description: A 19-year-old driver allegedly crashed a silver Holden Commodore into a row of parked cars in Middle Park, Melbourne, damaging 10 vehicles in total. After the collision, the teenager attempted to flee the scene but was detained by local residents who performed a citizen's arrest, pinning him down until police arrived. The driver was taken to hospital for assessment, with police continuing their investigation and charges yet to be laid. title: Adelaide barbershop torched by arsonists | 7NEWS
description: Three masked arsonists set fire to Solace Studio barbershop in Adelaide using accelerant, completely destroying the business that had only been open for five months. Owner Jemal Ward, 20, returned to find his shop in ruins after the 2am attack, which police believe may be linked to another suspicious fire at Thorngate 45 minutes later. Despite the devastation, Ward resumed cutting hair at the front of the burnt-out premises the same day. title: Bomb cyclone batters America's northeast | 7NEWS
description: A powerful winter storm, officially categorised as a bomb cyclone, has battered America's northeast from Maryland to Maine with up to 60 centimetres of snow and hurricane force winds. The blizzard, the strongest in a decade, has forced millions to stay home, knocked out power, closed schools and caused more than 8,000 flight cancellations and delays. New York officials say the storm could rank among the 10 worst in the past 150 years, with states of emergency declared across seven states and additional storms predicted to hit in the coming days.
